description.narrative:
In light of existing gender disparities and the current food crisis, requests for scaling up capacity development (CD) have been voiced by the FAO Member States. At the same time FAO has gone through a process of reorienting its strategies for CD and opting for amore participatory process than a mere one-way transfer of knowledge and skills; it recognizes pre-existing capacities, it builds on local resources (including people, skills, technologies and organizations) and it engages national institutions as partners in theCD process by identifying priorities and ownership in securing solutions to pressing agriculture and rural development issues. In acontext of limited human and financial resources, the new corporate strategy aims to forge partnerships with other CD actors in order to leverage and maximize impact on CD results at country level. FAO expects to play a catalytic role in CD activities through partnerships with national, (sub)regional and international actors. The idea of a network of gender experts was further described andexplored expected to be a cost-effective and powerful method to reinforce national capacities and ownership. It would combine the sharing of knowledge and lessons with linking demand for CD with “supply” of available expertise and experience, and it is seen as a possible vehicle for strengthening partnerships.
The expected result of the Network will be the enhanced capacities of Member States for gender mainstreaming in agriculture, food and nutrition security, and rural development projects, programmes and policies. Themechanism of a network of service providers requires developing options, identifying and consulting stakeholders and testing.
Oxfam Novib shares the interest that gender equality becomes an integral part of capacity development in the above mentioned themes. Moreover, key challenges identified by Oxfam Novib for scaling up gender mainstreaming especially in Sub Sahara Africa include the limited availability of high quality gender CD service providers and the lack of a quality assurance mechanism for the services. This iscombined with common perceptions of gender mainstreaming being irrelevant in economic development programmes, and an agenda of donors and western feminists. In order to contribute to addressing these constraints, Oxfam Novib is supporting the identification, design and mobilisation of a network of experts and organisations with expertise and experience in gender and capacity development.
